The data files are all simple text files, and the format of the data files is explained on the web page at https://people.sc.fsu.edu/~jburkardt/datasets/hartigan/hartigan.html Perform K-means clustering on file19.txt on the above web page. This file contains a multivariate mammals dataset; there are 9 columns and 66 rows.

Data cleanup

Think of what attributes, if any, you may want to omit from the dataset when you do the clustering. Indicate all of the attributes you removed before doing the clustering.

By seeing the correlation between the attributes,C&c,P&p,M&m are highly correlated pairs(above 90%).Similarly I&C,I&c,C&P,C&p,I&p,I&P are also correlated pairs.We can eliminate the one of the attributes among those highly correlate pairs(C&c,P&p,M&m) mentioned above before attempting clustering because it is like a repetition of feature/attribute.Actual method is whiten (decorrelate) the data by doing PCA, which is a best practise for k-means.Here I have created a data set after removing one of highly correlated attributes.The removed attributes are c,p and m.The remaining attributes used are I,i,C,P and M.The new data set is df.km.mod.

Hierarchical clustering

For this problem, you will use the “Languages spoken in Europe” dataset available from the Hartigan datasets.This dataset is available at https://people.sc.fsu.edu/~jburkardt/datasets/hartigan/file46.txt. Read this file into R.Note that you will have to pre-process the file since it is not, strictly speaking, a CSV file. Also make sure that the first column is recognized as a row label. (Hint: See the help on read.csv() and look at the row.names parameter.) Recognizing the first column as a row label is important because we want the country names to be printed as labels in the dendograms.

df.hc = read.table("file46.txt",skip=17,header = T)
rownames(df.hc) <- df.hc[,1]
df.hc[,1] <- NULL
df.hc

Run hierarchical clustering on the dataset using factoextra::eclust() method. Run the clustering algorithm for three linkages: single, complete, and average. Plot the dendogram associated with each linkage using fviz_dend(). Make sure that the labels (country names) are visible at the leafs of the dendogram.

k(the number of clusters to be generated) is taken as three in all of the linkages.

hr.single <- eclust(df.hc, "hclust", k = 3, hc_method="single")
fviz_dend(hr.single, show_labels=TRUE, palette="jco", as.ggplot=T)

hr.complete <- eclust(df.hc, "hclust", k = 3, hc_method="complete")
fviz_dend(hr.complete, show_labels=TRUE, palette="jco", as.ggplot=T)

hr.average <- eclust(df.hc, "hclust", k = 3, hc_method="average")
fviz_dend(hr.average, show_labels=TRUE, palette="jco", as.ggplot=T)

Examine each graph produced in (a) and understand the dendrogram. Notice which countries are clustered together as two-singleton clusters (i.e., two countries clustered together because they are very close to each other in the shared languages/s). For each linkage method, list all the two singleton clusters. For instance, {Great Britain, Ireland} form a two-singleton cluster since they share English as a common language.

Method of single linkage or nearest neighbour: Proximity between two clusters is the proximity between their two closest objects.All the two singleton clusters : {Great britain,Ireland},{Luxemburg,Switzerland},{Germany,Austria},{France,Belgium},{Denmark,Norway}

Method of complete linkage or farthest neighbour: Proximity between two clusters is the proximity between their two most distant objects.All the two singleton clusters : {Great britain,Ireland},{Luxemburg,Switzerland},{Germany,Austria},{France,Belgium},{Denmark,Norway}

Method of average .Proximity between two clusters is the arithmetic mean of all the proximities between the objects of one, on one side, and the objects of the other, on the other side.All the two singleton clusters : {Great britain,Ireland},{Luxemburg,Switzerland},{Germany,Austria},{France,Belgium},{Denmark,Norway},{Portugal,Spain}

Interpretation : For example in first dendogram the cluster containing denmark and norway is merged with sweden because the distance between that cluster from sweden is calculated using MIN proximity measure.Where as the same pair denmark and norway is merged with another cluster,where sweden is merged with cluster containing great britain and ireland.These changes happens in dendogram due to the changes in proximity calculation.Regardless of the proximity measures,for example {Germany,Austria} remains same in all three linkages, because of the LEAST distance between them.They are selected to merge at initial stage only due to the minimum dist between them.We have to select a linkage strategy according to what makes sense to our domain need.We can not say which is good which is bad.

Italy is clustered with a larger cluster in the single and average linkage, whereas in complete linkage it is clustered with a smaller cluster. Which linkage strategy do you think accurately reflects how Italy should be clustered? (Hint: Look at the raw data.) Justify your answer in 1-2 sentences.

In complete linkage Italy is merged with a cluster of France and Belgium.France and Belgium is two-singleton cluster, due to the reason that France and Belgium have a good percentage who speaks FR(am just using the code name here).In Italy majority speaks IT, but FR is only 11 percent, which is no way near to the statistics of what France and Belgium have in common(FR percentage is high).In my intuition we can not comment on the linkage strategy,just select the ones which makes sense.Actually Italy have to be paired to some branch which has Switzerland because IT percentage is highest in Switzerland(23),this happens in Single and Average linkage.So I think we have to pick either Single or Average linkage method, which makes sensible to an extent.

Let’s pick a hierarchical cluster that we will call pure, and let’s define purity as the linkage strategy that produces the most two-singleton clusters. Of the linkage methods you examined in (b), which linkage method would be considered pure by our definition?

Average linkage strategy produces six two-singleton clusters({Great britain,Ireland},{Luxemburg,Switzerland},{Germany,Austria},{France,Belgium},{Denmark,Norway},{Portugal,Spain}),which is the highest.So it is the most pure by definision above.

Provide observations on the shape of the clusters you got in (b)(i) to the plot of the first two principal components in (a)(ii). If the clusters are are similar, why? If they are not, why?

Clusters are not similar in PCA and in KMeans.In PCA the two clusters are along the maximum variance direction.But in KMeans its based on centroid and in each iteration centroid will move to the mean location etc.The idea of both algorithms are different.Apart from the idea of algorithms,PCA is used to reduce diamensions where as KMeans is used for clustering.We can do KMeans on large data sets after doing a PCA on the same.
